gement","fullItemName":"Stakeholder engagement"},{"id":"84ca6e0f-7674-5f70-b099-406d5c783d89","slug":"evidence-exclusion-criteria","fullItemName":"Evidence exclusion criteria"},{"id":"4ed139aa-715a-523d-8c0a-8f4e167d29df","slug":"organizational-behavioural-financial-barriers","fullItemName":"Organizational, behavioural and financial barriers"},{"id":"067e363b-53be-5584-a0e9-2bf38e519877","slug":"declarations-of-interest","fullItemName":"Declarations of interest"}]},{"id":"045ecabb-df97-5df3-b561-ecddea4b7b17","fullItemName":"References","slug":"references","subChapters":[]}]},"parentChapter":{"id":"6d45128d-30db-5879-917a-4a6e682fa7e9","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management"},"subChapters":[{"id":"adf7b601-1ebf-5590-8d79-415b65ac7146","slug":"management","fullItemName":"Management","depth":3,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 86d3507d-afc3-4f5a-b86f-a71b00f93432 --><h3>How should I manage women with suspected urinary tract infection associated with visible or non-visible haematuria?</h3><!-- end field 86d3507d-afc3-4f5a-b86f-a71b00f93432 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item e98f1035-31b5-488a-90c2-a71b00f9352f --><!-- begin field 79c88fab-c699-4298-b076-a71b00f93432 --><ul><li>Manage acute UTI depending on specific clinical situation (ensuring that a urine culture has been sent prior to starting antibiotics) as described in the sections on:<ul><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/management/uti-no-visible-haematuria-not-pregnant-or-catheterized/#management\">Uncomplicated acute UTI (not pregnant or catheterized)</a></li><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/management/recurrent-uti-no-visible-haematuria-not-pregnant-or-catheterized/#management\">Recurrent UTI (not pregnant or catheterized)</a></li><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/management/uti-in-pregnancy-no-visible-haematuria/#management\">UTI in pregnancy</a></li><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/management/asymptomatic-bacteriuria-in-pregnancy/#asymptomatic-bacteriuria-in-pregnancy\">Asymptomatic bacteriuria in pregnancy</a></li><li><a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/management/uti-with-catheter-no-haematuria/#management\">Catheter associated UTI (not pregnant)</a></li></ul></li><li>Re-test urine after completing treatment with an appropriate antibiotic — if haematuria is persistent consider possible underlying causes.<ul><li>If a urological cancer is suspected arrange an urgent 2-week wait referral.<ul><li>For more information on when to suspect a urological cancer, see the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/urological-cancers-recognition-referral/\">Urological cancers - recognition and referral</a>.</li></ul></li><li>If a gynaecological cancer is suspected arrange an urgent 2-week wait referral.<ul><li>For more information on when to suspect a gynaecological cancer, see the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/gynaecological-cancers-recognition-referral/\">Gynaecological cancers - recognition and referral</a>.</li></ul></li><li>If chronic kidney disease is suspected, arrange further investigations and consider the need for referral to secondary care.<ul><li>For more information, see the CKS topic on <a class=\"topic-reference external-reference\" href=\"/topics/chronic-kidney-disease/\">Chronic kidney disease</a>.</li></ul></li><li>If haematuria persists after appropriate treatment of UTI in pregnancy – urgently discuss ongoing management with obstetrics. </li><li>If the underlying cause is unclear discuss the need for further investigations/referral with urology.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 79c88fab-c699-4298-b076-a71b00f93432 --><!-- end item e98f1035-31b5-488a-90c2-a71b00f9352f -->","subChapters":[{"id":"9fd5b75d-946c-540c-96c1-9e133c4ab9e0","slug":"basis-for-recommendation-10f","fullItemName":"Basis for recommendation","depth":4,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 788908eb-863f-4e36-a8ec-a71b00f93438 --><h4>Basis for recommendation</h4><!-- end field 788908eb-863f-4e36-a8ec-a71b00f93438 -->","summary":null,"htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 10fb2b10-5084-473a-a1ef-a71b00f93438 --><!-- begin field f7ea678d-d190-4c69-bd2e-a71b00f93438 --><p>The recommendations on the management of haematuria associated with UTI are based on the clinical guidelines <em>Asymptomatic Microscopic Hematuria in Women</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">ACOG, 2017a</a>], <em>Recurrent Urinary Tract Infection</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">Epp, 2017</a>], <em>Suspected cancer: recognition and referral</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">NICE, 2017b</a>], <em>Urological Infections </em>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">EAU, 2018</a>], <em>and UK standards for microbiological investigations. Investigation of urine</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">PHE, 2018a</a>] and expert opinion in review articles [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">Sharp, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">Hole, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">BMJ Best Practice, 2018d</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">BMJ Best Practice, 2018d</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">Gbinigie, 2018</a>].</p><ul><li>Haematuria (visible and non-visible) can occur in association with acute cystitis but may also be caused by non-infective conditions such as malignancy, urolithiasis, renal disease or trauma (for example following urinary catheterisation). Apparent transient haematuria may be due to menstruation [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">Hole, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">ACOG, 2017a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">BMJ Best Practice, 2018c</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">BMJ Best Practice, 2018e</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">BMJ Best Practice, 2018d</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">EAU, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">Gbinigie, 2018</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">PHE, 2018a</a>].</li><li>As underlying conditions causing haematuria can be serious, the presence of haematuria should be considered to be a red flag and prompt consideration of the need for further investigation/referral [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">Hole, 2014</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">Quinlan, 2017</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">BMJ Best Practice, 2018c</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">Gbinigie, 2018</a>].</li></ul><h5>Referring to exclude urological and gynaecological cancer</h5><ul><li>The recommendation to arrange an urgent 2-week wait referral in suspected cancer is based on the NICE guideline <em>Suspected cancer: recognition and referral</em> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">NICE, 2017b</a>].</li></ul><h5>Investigation and referral for chronic kidney disease</h5><ul><li>This recommendation has been extrapolated from the NICE guideline <em>Chronic kidney disease in adults: assessment and management</em>  [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/urinary-tract-infection-lower-women/references/\">NICE, 2014</a>].</li></ul><h5>Haematuria in pregnancy</h5><ul><li>The recommendation that haematuria in pregnancy should be discussed urgently with a specialist is pragmatic given that serious underlying conditions (such as pre-eclampsia and renal pathology) may cause haematuria in pregnancy.</li></ul><!-- end field f7ea678d-d190-4c69-bd2e-a71b00f93438 --><!-- end item 10fb2b10-5084-473a-a1ef-a71b00f93438 -->","subChapters":[]}]}]}}},"staticQueryHashes":["3666801979"]}